Commentary Text: Mohsin Khan to Russell, out Caught by Hooda!! Mohsin with a potential game-killing blow! Dre Russ has been sent packing. To be fair, he never looked in rhythm in his brief stay at the crease, LSG bowled brilliantly to him and it's another clever delivery that ends his innings. Slower off-cutter, wider again and Russell has to reach this, can't gather the required power on the loft and ends up slicing it a bit. Commentary Text: Ravi Bishnoi to Billings, out Stumped!! Strong comeback from Bishnoi who has the last laugh! Probably got a feedback after that last ball, and went back to classical leg spin bowling. Slowed down the googly considerably and beat Billings in flight, the batter was way down for the big shot and got beaten on the inside edge. He was so far down that it was almost a run out. A hot-and-cold innings from Billings, started well and seemed to be in full flow but those wickets around him clearly put him off. Huge blow for KKR. Billings st de Kock b Ravi Bishnoi 36(24) [4s-2 6s-3]

Commentary Text: Stoinis to Shreyas Iyer, out Caught by Hooda!! Stoinis breaks the partnership! This is a fielder's wicket though because the mishit went miles in the air towards deep mid-wicket. Long-on and deep mid-wicket were both converging but it seemed like the ball would evade both. Hooda, stationed near cow corner judges it well and gets across to time his tumble perfectly, clinging onto a massive game-changing catch. Cleverly bowled by Stoinis too, another slower ball into the surface and it meant that Iyer got more height than distance on the slog. The KKR captain goes immediately after his fifty and LSG are now on top. Shreyas Iyer c Hooda b Stoinis 50(29) [4s-4 6s-3]

Commentary Text: Mohsin Khan to Venkatesh Iyer, out Caught by de Kock!! Wow! Rename this day as Quinton de Kock Day. He can do no wrong today and might have just pulled off the catch of the season. Nips back in from a good length, Iyer is prodding forward to drive without accounting for the movement, the ball takes the inside edge and flies to the right, de Kock dives full length and is horizontal to the ground when he takes the one-handed blinder.
